On September 30, 1928, that is, exactly 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the isolation of penicillin from molds was not Fleming&#39;s first discovery.
A few years earlier, being with a cold, he sowed mucus from his own nose on a Petri dish (this is a glass lid in which experiments with bacteria are carried out) and a few days later found that the bacteria there had been destroyed.
In almost the same way, he discovered penicillin by chance.
Fleming&#39;s name was included in the list of the 100 most prominent personalities in the history of mankind.
Its discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases that were previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene ...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, Parisian newspapers wrote: &quot;He did more than dozens of divisions to defeat fascism and liberate France.&quot;
According to experts, Fleming&#39;s discovery of the world&#39;s first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people on Earth.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated, and a week later his ashes were buried in London&#39;s famous St. Paul&#39;s Cathedral.
Where, by the way, my wife and I paid attention to this talkative Russian-speaking guide.
And a few years later, we had a chance to observe the full-length statue of Alexander Fleming in the most unexpected place for this in the capital of Spain.
There, next to the main bullfighting arena Plaza de Toros de Las Ventas, the most famous Spanish matadors erected a monument to the man, whose efforts, in their opinion, saved the lives of hundreds of outstanding bullfighting masters.
By the way, this, in my opinion, very interesting porcelain work was found by me in the same place, in Madrid, but at a different time and not at all for this reason.
