AfD has become the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany is breaking another record in popularity, and Angela Merkel&#39;s ratings are falling.
Apparently, the people of Germany have begun to get seriously tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country has become a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The most obvious evidence of this is the latest opinion polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party &quot;Alternative for Germany&quot; is becoming more and more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
The AfD broke another record this week, moving up to second place in the popular sympathy rating.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of their popularity, have managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one percentage point gap can be attributed to a statistical error, but at the same time, it should be noted that the AfD, created in 2013, from a small group of Eurosceptic economists has managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings is still held by the ruling bloc of the CSU / CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency for points to be lost - back in April, support for the Angela Merkel bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth term in a row, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent less than last year.
We add that the Social Democrats are followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
Evolution of &quot;Alternatives&quot;
The party &quot;Alternative for Germany&quot; was created in September 2012 on the basis of the group &quot;Alternative choice 2013&quot;, which included immigrants from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially stood in opposition to the government&#39;s course, but at first it was engaged only in economic issues, including the problems of the euro and interaction within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed the &quot;sponsoring&quot; of the weak EU economies by Germany, did not rule out the possibility of a return to the German mark and the country&#39;s complete withdrawal from the European Union.
Against the background of the deepening immigration crisis, the AfD&#39;s political platform expanded.
In 2013, the group formed into a full-fledged party, which occupied the niche of Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, having received 94 parliamentary seats (out of 709).
