The deadline for the death of the universe
The universe will survive for another 140 billion years, which is ten times the age of the observable world, equal to about 13.8 billion years.
The research by an international team of scientists has been uploaded to the arXiv.org electronic preprint library and is sent for publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, according to the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
Experts came to similar conclusions by observing about ten million galaxies using the HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) telescope of the Subaru telescope.
By tracing the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observed world, scientists, working within the standard cosmological model ΛCDM (Λ Cold Dark Matter), estimated the expansion rate of the universe, which turned out to be slightly slower than previously thought.
In a press release, the Subaru Observatory notes that the observations made it possible to obtain a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the Universe, and the accounting of data from the European Space Telescope Planck clarified the restrictions imposed on the parameters of ΛCDM.
In July, scientists simulated the possible death of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues had presented new arguments that the observed world would cease to exist in 22 billion years as a result of the Great Rip.
